<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1899-09-06T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1899-09-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="88" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d88">
                            <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                        <persName type="to">Vignaud</persName></hi>.</head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1899-09-06"><hi rend="italic">September 6,
                                        1899</hi></date>.</dateline>
                                <seg rendition="#left">No. 664.]</seg></opener>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to inclose, for your
                                confidential information, copies of instructions I have sent under
                                this date to the United States ambassadors at London, Berlin, and
                                St. Petersburg in reference to the desire of this Government that
                                the Governments of Great Britain, Germany, and Russia make formal
                                declaration of an “open-door” policy in the territories held by them
                                in China.</p>
                            <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi></signed></closer>
                            <frus:attachment>
                                <head><hi rend="italic">Inclosures</hi>.</head>
                                <p>To London, No. 205, September 6, 1899, printed <ref target="#pg_131">page 131</ref>.</p>
                                <p>To Berlin, No. 927, September 6, 1899, printed <ref target="#pg_129">page 129</ref>.</p>
                                <p>To St. Petersburg, No. 82, September 6, 1899, printed <ref target="#pg_140">page 140</ref>.</p>
                            </frus:attachment>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>